✅ Phase 1: Understand Power BI Architecture (Day 1–2)
Goal: Know the components and how they interact.
Topics:

Power BI Desktop: For report creation and modeling.
Power BI Service: For publishing, sharing, and collaboration.
Power BI Gateway: For connecting on-premises data to the cloud.
Power BI Mobile: For viewing dashboards on mobile devices.

Action Plan:

Watch Microsoft’s official Power BI Overview video.
Read documentation on Power BI ecosystem.
Create a simple report in Power BI Desktop and publish it to Power BI Service.


✅ Phase 2: Data Sources & Connectivity (Day 3–4)
Goal: Learn how to connect Power BI to different data sources.
Topics:

Connecting to Excel, CSV, SQL Server, Web APIs, and Azure.
Difference between Import Mode and DirectQuery.
Understand Live Connection for Analysis Services.

Action Plan:

Practice connecting Power BI to:

A local Excel file.
A SQL Server database.
A public API (e.g., COVID-19 data).


Explore Data Gateway setup for on-premises data.


✅ Phase 3: Data Transformation with Power Query (Day 5–7)
Goal: Clean and shape data before modeling.
Topics:

Power Query Editor basics.
Common transformations:

Remove duplicates, filter rows, merge queries.


Introduction to M Language (Power Query formula language).

Action Plan:

Import messy data and clean it using Power Query.
Create custom columns using M expressions.
Learn Query Folding for performance optimization.


✅ Phase 4: Data Modeling (Day 8–10)
Goal: Build a strong data model for analysis.
Topics:

Relationships:

One-to-many, many-to-many.


Star vs Snowflake Schema:

Why star schema is preferred.


Fact and Dimension Tables:

Role in analytical models.



Action Plan:

Design a Star Schema for a sample sales dataset.
Create relationships in Power BI Desktop.
Use Manage Relationships and Model View effectively.


✅ Resources

Microsoft Learn: Power BI Learning Path
YouTube: Guy in a Cube (Power BI tutorials).
Practice datasets: Kaggle or Microsoft sample datasets.


